Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Chop the @potatoes{450%grams} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel).

Pop the chunks onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @olive oil{}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, sprinkle over the @dried rosemary{1%sachet}, then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-35%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

In the meantime, trim the @courgette{1%unit}, then quarter lengthways. Chop into 1cm chunks.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{} in a #frying pan{} on high heat. When hot, add the courgette and cook until charred, ~{6-8%minutes} total. Turn only every couple of mins.

Once cooked, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then transfer the courgette to a #bowl{} and set aside.

While the courgette chars, cut the @medium tomato{1%unit} into 1cm chunks.

Tear the @ciabatta{1%unit} into roughly 2cm chunks.

Pop the ciabatta onto a baking tray in a single layer. Drizzle with @olive oil{}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and toss to coat well.

When the potatoes have around 10 mins left, bake the croutons on the middle shelf until golden, ~{8-10%minutes}, then remove from the oven and set aside.

Meanwhile, in a large bowl, combine the @sun-dried tomato paste{25%grams}, @honey{15%grams}, @balsamic vinegar{24%milliliters} and @olive oil{2%tbsp} for the dressing. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> TIP: If your honey has hardened, pop it in a bowl of hot water for 1 min.

Once your courgette is charred, toss the tomato and courgette through the dressing. Set aside to macerate.

Wipe out the pan used for the courgette and pop back on medium-high heat with a drizzle of @olive oil{}.

Once hot, lay the @Serrano ham{3%slices} into the pan and fry until crisp, ~{2-3%minutes} each side.

Once crispy, transfer to a #plate{} covered in #kitchen paper{}.

When everything's ready, add the potatoes, croutons and @baby leaf mix{50%grams} to the #salad bowl{} and toss to evenly coat.

Share the salad between your serving bowls.

Snap the Serrano ham into shards and serve on top of the salad to finish.

Enjoy!